3 CHAPTER 397
4 MAINE BLUE ECONOMY CENTER
5 §13401. Definitions
6 As used in this chapter, unless the context otherwise indicates, the following terms
7 have the following meanings.
8 1. Blue economy sector. "Blue economy sector" means the aggregate of persons
9 engaged in any economic activity relating to aquaculture and marine vegetation, marine
10 biotechnology, ocean data and marine research, resilient coastal infrastructure, sustainable
11 boat building or marine propulsion for the purpose of improving human, animal and
12 environmental health, including business, manufacturing, research, education and other
13 activities.
14 2. Board. "Board" means the Board of Directors of the Maine Blue Economy Center
15 established in section 13403, subsection 2.
16 3. Bond. "Bond" means a bond or note or other evidence of indebtedness authorized
17 under this chapter, whether issued under or pursuant to a bond resolution, trust indenture,
18 loan or other security agreement.
19 4. Center. "Center" means the Maine Blue Economy Center established in section
20 13402.
21 5. Certified blue economy business. "Certified blue economy business" means a
22 business that has been certified by the board as being eligible to receive investments, grants,
23 loans and incentives from the fund.
24 6. Fund. “Fund” means the Maine Blue Economy Fund established in section 13404.
25 7. Real and personal property. "Real and personal property" means properties and
26 assets purchased by the center or transferred to the center from federal, state, local and
27 private entities and individuals.
28 §13402. Maine Blue Economy Center established
29 The Maine Blue Economy Center is established as a body corporate and politic and a
30 public instrumentality of the State, exercising public and essential governmental functions.
31 The center is an independent legal entity and is not a department, agency or instrumentality
32 of State Government for purposes of administrative law or budgeting, and the debts,
33 liabilities and obligations of the center are not debts, liabilities or obligations of the State.
34 The center shall leverage and expand the State's blue economy sector by:
35 1. Central entity. Serving as the central entity and coordinating organization for blue
36 economy sector initiatives on behalf of the State and working in collaboration with
37 governmental entities, trade associations, institutions of higher education, research
38 institutions and other entities to provide for the growth of the blue economy sector;
Page 1 - 132LR3009(01)

1 2. Data collection and publication. Gathering and analyzing data that inform
2 decisions, measure progress and identify new opportunities for the blue economy sector.
3 The center shall publish the data through accessible tools, such as an online portal;
4 3. Revenue to center. Applying for and accepting contributions of any source of
5 money, property, labor or any other things of value, including federal, state and nonprofit
6 funding opportunities for the State's blue economy sector;
7 4. Workforce retention and attraction. Facilitating the creation of a highly skilled
8 workforce and attracting and retaining workers in the blue economy sector. The center
9 shall promote and assist in the placement of internships, apprenticeships and
10 interdisciplinary trainings at certified blue economy businesses in the State;
11 5. Business development and attraction. Coordinating the State's business
12 development and business attraction programs and organizations to increase the number of
13 certified blue economy businesses in the State;
14 6. Targeted workforce analyses. Conducting targeted workforce analyses by
15 assessing workforce barriers and future needs in the State’s blue economy sector;
16 7. Planning for growth. Creating and executing a strategic plan for growth in the
17 State's blue economy sector;
18 8. Education and training. Enhancing science, technology, engineering and
19 mathematics education and engagement in kindergarten to grade 12 and higher education
20 curricula;
21 9. Research and development. Facilitating increased research and development
22 activity relating to the blue economy sector at the State's public and private research
23 organizations;
24 10. Public engagement. Facilitating community outreach and educational
25 programming for the people of the State related to the blue economy sector;
26 11. Marketing and promotion. Marketing the State's blue economy sector both
27 within and outside of the State to attract companies, business investment and talent to the
28 State; and
29 12. Administering fund. Administering the fund.
